Anonymous Thu 29 Mar 2018 01:56:32 No.14833757 Report
Quoted By:
>>14833654
Because they're heavily structured.
It may be awkward to do in the present tense, but try to write like you're remembering it rather than describing it while it's happening. You (and others) probably don't really care about the procedure or sequence of events. You're drinking, partying, and anticipating, and it's going to be snapshots and moments that you remember. Your life during the wedding ceremony isn't the ceremony, it's the little things that happen while you perform it.

Quoted By: >>14835263 >>14835313
>>14835007
So this is a quote I've stolen from Yahtzee, who himself is repeating his writing teacher, but ultimately I've heard paraphrased and reworded so many times (by one of my own professors as well) that the idea simply just has that much merit.

>"Is this the most interesting thing about your character's life? No? Then why aren't we hearing about THAT instead?"
Basically, if you know shit is about to be boring, then unless you're about to hit the reader with some pivotal lore/details you need to get with the business and ditch whatever you're doing. Rewrite if necessary, to avoid scenes that simply plod along entirely. Time skips, much like tropes and cliches, are entirely acceptable tools within the writer's arsenal. You just have to use them right. Just don't use them so heavily that readers are cross referencing how many times the word "tomorrow" and "today" or "later"/"earlier" show up in your shit just so they have a frame of reference for the current time in the story.

Do different drawing exercises. Just doodle for fun if you need to relax and rest. Find other artist to be drawing buddies with so they can help and critique you. You can even try still life drawings if you want something more fun. Watching artist who stream their drawings might help you pick up some stuff too. This is important, don't compare your progress to other artists. It's not a race and treating it like so will just depress you. While /ic/ is useful, take what they say with a grain of salt given how bitter that place can be towards new artists.
